You can always adjust captures in post, but if the camera doesn't capture enough data in the first place, there's nothing you can do.

snippet.textDisplay: Saying the iPhone is the best camera is like saying Lamborghinis are the best cars.  False.  Sorry linus, but every image that came from the iPhone was blurry when there are light sources in the frame and inadequate when you are trying to mimic what humans actually see.  iPhones aren't as good at keeping TRUE DETAIL.  When I look at an iPhone shot I can tell it's an iPhone shot because there's a large blur and smear effect around lights, a horrible amount of shadows and highlights lost, and a disgusting amount of the true colors lost.  The iPhone may seem like the images are better but when it comes to any contrast/ conflict between colors and brightness, the image turns out very poor and you can tell the image no longer looks like the original subject.  My Indian friend posed next to his Caucasian friend and I took a picture with his iPhone pro max (yea he's a rich Indian) and the skin tones looked eerily similar to his Caucasian friend.  The iPhone wants to normalize all the colors, while the pixel 4 properly documents the shot.  If you look at the image of the girl in the resteraunt.  The pixel 4 looks sharp and crisp on the subject, while the iPhone looks very blurry and almost like you are looking through a dirty price if saran wrap.  If ur gonna make iPhone videos praising them just go work for Apple and make commercials using 50k worth of video equipment and expensive lenses then claim it was "shot on iphone'

snippet.textDisplay:
None of this really matters when most people's use case is uploading images to social media where they get resized and reprocessed anyway. No one is going to agonize over the detail of a building in the distance when they spend about a 1/8th of a second looking at the photo as the flick through their Instagram feed. Most decent phones will produce perfectly fine images for this purpose. The problem is this belief people have now that mobile cameras have replaced even a decent point and shoot. Having worked in commercial printing for the last 13 years the best example of this in high school yearbooks, as the shift from compact cameras to mobile phones has lead to a serious degradation of image quality over the last decade. Even worse are those people wanting to print a mobile camera shot to a poster or canvas, and they aren't happy it looks grainy or it lacks detail from all the artifacting, despite how much I warn them.

The bigger and more relevant point of difference between the Pixel 4 and iPhone 11, is the part of the video that was covered the least - the video camera. Unlike the still camera, which is largely restricted to personal use, the video camera is something that can be used to create legitimate content.

snippet.textDisplay:
iPhone 11 has the best video. A level above the rest. However, Deep fusion only beat the others when it comes to night shots, and that is if you like boosted shadows all the time! I for one, would want my night sky too look properly dark and black, unlike some of the deep fusion shots on the iphone.

Huawei mate 30 pro has the worst misses. Both in Photo and video. Various dogshit unusable photos.

Pixel 4 still has the crown in photos. Neutral, accurate. Contrasty look is nice. Who would want soft faded look over contrast vibrant look? Just compare the last few sets of photos, James' portrait looks best on pixel. The sunset at the carpark was also best on pixel 4.

Note 10 is just in between pixel and iphone. Pretty average. It did white balance and sharpness better than deep fusion in many zoom in photos. For example in the photo of the ent and the dwarf, pixel 4 and note 10 did great. iphone deepfusion looks grainy af

The indoors bar shot with a strong backlight. Pixel 4 exposed the main subject correctly, and that's what matters most. Not the back ground. iPhone tried to correct the exposure to both expose for the background and the subject. Resulting in ugly faded wash out look for the main subject with weird skin tones, meanwhile the back is still unusably over exposed. Resulting in an overall bad output. Mate 30 pro is just dogshit in this example.

Overall I would pick note 10 for overall, pixel 4 for photos, iPhone 11 for video. deep fusion misses are too unreliable for a phone this expensive.
